< Text>
DC Computers in Hillcrest is the best computer store in San Diego. I honestly like it better than the Apple Store. They have MacBooks, MacBook Pros, iMacs, MacBook Airs, Mac Pros, Mac Minis + PCs for Sale, like IBM ThinkPads and Lenovo laptops.

I got a MacBook Pro from them for my personal computer and they upgraded the RAM and the SSD Hard Drive. For my business, DC provided me with a powerful 27 inch iMac, and even replaced a cracked screen on a laptop for me and saved the data.

Plus, they have some of the best deals on iPhones & iPads in town.

They are so cool and understanding, and their customer service is terrific.

Thank you DC Computers!</Text>

<rating>1</rating>< review>
I had a few issues with my gaming rig and took it in to get looked at a few weeks ago. I dropped off my computer acting foolishly like I had no idea what was wrong with it. I needed a little bit more help when it comes to certain things with my custom built rig. I came back the next day thinking they called me in to bring my monitor since my BIOS would not come up? When I brought in the monitor, guy at the front counter said it would be looked at by Monday? I simply repeated myself letting him know that I was picking up my computer and wanted to see what was wrong with it. As soon as I gave him the specs. He mumbled a bit and I could tell he was trying to blow me off at first. Started throwing numbers at me $1,500-$1,900 for a new build that I didn't want? I asked him what type of upgrades would be possible?? Younger guy working in the back on the computers was very nice and knowledgeable when I asked about CPU and motherboards. I walked out of DC Computers more disappointed than when I brought it in. I understand he has a service to provide, but not like that. Needs better customer service.< /review>

<date>1530240188724<//date>< Text>
We used Englund's Catering Service for our wedding and, simply stated, the food and service knocked our expectations out of the park.  Derry, the head manager, was super polite and easy to work with - there were some points throughout the planning where it was difficult to get into contact with him, however, he is a very busy person and when time got closer, he gave us his FULL attention.  Englund's catering service was willing to travel all the way to Fairfax, CA for our wedding at Deer Park Villa.  The service has worked at this venue before and this provided a great 1-2 punch for our guests.  I would recommend Englund's Catering Service to any wedding in the bay area - affordable and valuable.<//Text>

< text>
I love going to this store. Owen and his team are helpful, friendly, knowledgable and easy to work with. They work quickly on things like string replacement and re-hair of my bow. Today I went in to upgrade my violin. Kendra and Daniel spent a great deal of time assisting me in that process. There were a number of violins to choose from. Kendra was awesome. She was patient while I made my selection and even played my top choices for me so I could hear them as a listener. Thank you Owen, Daniel, and Kendra. I love my new violin and appreciate the service you have provided over the last year.< /text>

< review>
The staff members are really welcoming ^-^ They also offer classes in the space opposite the shop. I am currently taking classes right now and I am really happy to be under the tutelage of my teacher. Their teachers are very talented and they play beautifully. Apart from violins, they also sell shoulder rests, rosin, mutes, books, etc. You may also have your violin repaired here as there are luthiers available. The practice rooms are relatively sound proof, sound does still seep out but it isnt bothersome during lessons. I would like to mention that the shop is located upstairs and there is a sign posted on the door so the entrance is easily spotted. I really do love this shop and Ive had nothing but good experiences here ^-^<//review>

< review>
We had a great violin buying experience for my daughter. Her teacher recommended that she try instruments at this this shop and the more established shop in Hollywood. We were shown about an equal number of instruments at both shops, but in the end the selections didn't compare. We were so pleased at LA Violin Shop that both my daughter and her teacher bought new instruments there. Her new violin is fantastic, priced very well for its value, and they took not one but two trade-ins. Since we spent a fair amount of time trying violins and bows, I appreciated the comfort of the room. This was about 6 weeks ago and we're still pleased with the decision. We drove in from the Inland Empire, and it was well-worth the trip. I recommend them.<//review>

< review>
I came into the shop wishing to rent a cello for a short-term stay in LA. I was pleasantly surprised to be given an extremely nice-sounding cello to test out before deciding to rent one. I decided to go with it and was charged an extremely reasonable price, making it realistic for me to pursue music in LA without my own instrument. I used the cello for a professional recording session as well as a purely acoustic session and it worked great for both. If I ever need to buy a cello I am coming here. Not to mention that the staff was extremely friendly, gave me information about not only the classical music community but also local rock groups to help me get started in the area, and offered delicious coffee and chocolates. Highly recommended!</review>

<rating>4< /rating>< Text>
Horchata and two tacos were about $8.7.  I've never had burria before but it's some sort of meat stew so having it in a taco was cool! Both lengua and burria tacos were a tad overseasoned but came out with a piping, hot, and generous portion of meat.  The horchata was creamy and sweet, almost like drinking cocoa puff cereal milk with a hint of cinnamon.  Meal comes with a small tray of tortilla chips.

Would come back if near the area.</Text>

<gmapID>0x80858716d267d99f:0xe42021c9a0a5295b</gmapID><text>I was making a necklace for my roommate, and needed a clasp and some jump rings.  I've gone to another store by my work, but I knew I wouldn't have time during my work day.  Luckily, The Hobby Company is close by to my apartment, and made things very convenient for me.

<Rating>4<//Rating><text>I do a lot of my shopping at Safeway, due to the selection of pantry and frozen items being a better fit for me, but this Lucky wins for produce hands-down.

Not only was the apparent quality of the produce better, they also had a much better variety. I usually have to go to Trader Joe's for apples to my liking, but they had at least seven or eight varieties, one of which was Kiku - it has a much better flavor than the standard "sweet, crisp" apples you normally find. I'm hopeful I'll be able to get some Jonagold or Braeburn here later in the season. There was also a label for Cripps apples, though none to be found when I was there. The produce section also has helpful notes for things like the flavor profile for apples and what to look for in choosing cucumbers, which is great if you don't have much experience there.

Lines weren't too long, even on a Friday evening, which is nice. Plenty of baggers, though I i bagged my own since i had reusable bags and that reduces risk for the baggers in the current conditions. I did miss the clearly marked sanitized/unsanitized carts and hand sanitizer station from my Safeway,</text><pics>None< /pics>< Response>

It's Mother's day..My youngest Son and his girl came down from Sonora..there's no where to go out to eat.. but a few places are doing take out today..
( because of this darn Covid19)..
Our faves were not...So we decided to try a new place...This Place! We ordered 4 sandwiches...it's the first time EVER that EVERYONE was completely satisfied and boasting this to be our "new" favorite place!
My husband and son both had Tri tip..
They couldn't say enough about the awesome chipolte flavor. My daughter in law to be had Turkey cranberry pesto and usually doesn't finish an entire sandwich..but did today! Myself..being bold an adventurous...and also a Chef and sandwich slinger from Waaaay back... I  did a blind order.."please have the Chef create for me the sandwich he/she would have for his/her own lunch...Can I just say..OMGoodness!
Since I didn't order a name or number I will describe it...the most tasty, moist, thin sliced chicken with just a hint of rosemary. Served on a toasted Panini with Fresh crisp greens..thin sliced red onion and an awesome pesto! The French fries were seasoned just right that they needed no catsup or ranch! Even the passion tea was fresh tasting and NOT bitter...some places don't brew fresh daily..this place DOES! SO...for the first time EVER...from Me...a Chef and culinary graduate from 1980... The lady who ALWAYS sends her steak back cuz it's never right! Basically...the bold broad who makes you "prove" that you ARE and have the right to call yourself a Chef..
I give this Classic but Unique Joint A
5star rating!!!</review>

Renee Jones< /username>
< Review>
It was our happy fortune to turn right in Oakdale, instead of our usual left, heading to Yosemite.  We were looking for coffee.  Instead, we found our new favorite cafe, Cottonwood Cafe.  It's a family-run business, with cheerful, friendly staff, excellent cooks in the kitchen, a delicious variety of meals on the menu, and prompt and courteous service.  The lovely  outdoor patio beckoned us, but on that 100 degree day, it beckoned flies also, so we ate inside.  We enjoyed the music (not too loud, so we could converse), and the cool, well-ventilated room.  And REALLY enjoyed our food.  Thank you, Cottonwood Cafe.  We'll be back on our next trip to the mountains.< /Review>

< UserId.>
112679253343342471631</UserId.>
<Name>Francesca Immediato<//Name><Date>1534316779766</Date><Rate>5<//Rate><Review>Cottonwood Caf√©
Some people eat to survive while others eat to live; the line between the two, is not a thin one. Some of the largest factors that go into how good a meal will be is the amount of love and passion put into a dish. At the Cottonwood Caf√©, there is no question on whether Jay the owner/chef has a passion for the art work he has created because you can taste the love in every bite you take. Every single ingredient on his well-dressed plates from the entr√©e to the salad to the soup are so clearly thought out. The first dish I had the privilege of eating at this underappreciated hole-in-the-wall restaurant was a chicken mango grilled cheese with bacon and avocado, a dish I continue to return to. Every part of the sandwiches served here are planned to a T, all of the sauces are hand-made with select local ingredients, all of the produce used including the fruit served with every dish is always perfectly ripe, as I said, clearly thought out. But the sandwiches are not the only dishes that deserve a spot light because everything served here is absolutely amazing. The soups here are hand-made to deliciousness (and dippable) I have trouble choosing between the roasted red pepper and Thai soup. The entrees are to die for, I also have trouble believing I will ever eat a more delicious, succulent rendition of Chicken Parmesan in my whole life. Every bite you take is a masterpiece in its own way because that is the way it was designed. Not only is the food so beyond that of the local competitors the atmosphere and owners make going to the Cottonwood Caf√© an experience that should not be neglected. Every time you take precious time out of your day to visit, in my opinion the best restaurant in the area, your time is treated as such. This isn‚Äôt a franchise or place you can visit in nearly every city or state. Every experience you have here is new because not only is the food made to feel important but so are you. You don‚Äôt have to be a foodie to appreciate what Jay puts in front of you, all you have to do is have taste buds. Honestly I could go on for pages and pages about what makes this restaurant so amazing and how the food just sweeps you off your feet but the best way to find out is to go yourself, I promise you it will be worth it.<//Review>< pictures>
